 Owino added that preparations and how approaches to the game are the match deciders, with the current football dynamics. “In football there is no more big and small teams nowadays but your preparation towards it is the key,” said Owino, popularly known as Calabar for his stellar performance against Nigeria in the Nigerian town as Kenya held the Super Eagles in a past World Cup qualifier. Greece based Abud Omar and Real Murcia’s Isamail Gonzalez have also put a  brave face ahead of the crucial match, underlining it will be an open game for either sides.  “They have a good team and we also havea good one so we will play to the best of our ability and see the outcome,” he noted, with Omar saying they have a chance of showing the world Kenya can play in the biggest football fiesta.  Kenya will tackle Mali tomorrow at 10pm with the return leg awaiting them three days later in Nairobi. Also Read: In another group E match tomorrow, Rwanda’s Amavubi stars will host Uganda from 7pm. Mali are currently leading the group with four points with Kenya and Uganda following in the second and third place both with two points as Rwanda sit last with a point.  Video Of The Day: Former sports CS Hassan Wario convicted over Rio games scam